HEADWORD: Diptera
<hw>Dip"te*ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n. pl.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr.
Gr. <?/ with two wings, <grk>di-</grk> = <grk>di`s-</grk> twice + <?/
feather, wing: cf. F. <ets>dipt⟦egrave⟧re</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An extensive order of insects having only two
functional wings and two balancers, as the house fly, mosquito, etc.
They have a suctorial proboscis, often including two pairs of sharp
organs (mandibles and maxill⟦ae⟧) with which they pierce the skin of
animals. They undergo a complete metamorphosis, their larv⟦ae⟧ (called
maggots) being usually without feet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

